                <note rend="inline" type="source">816.00 Revolutions/22½: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Minister in El Salvador</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Curtis</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1931-12-05T13:00:00-05:00"
                            >December 5, 1931—1 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>60. It appears from your telegrams that the revolution was organized and carried
                    out by younger army officers. You also mention, however, that General Martínez,
                    who is presumably identical with Vice President Martínez, is assisting actively
                    in the movement.</p>
                <p>Please report fully by telegraph as to part played in the revolution by the Vice
                    President and by the three <hi rend="italic">designados</hi> and whether any of
                    the latter are still in San Salvador, or whether they accompanied President
                    Araujo to Santa Ana.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Stimson</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
